    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that coin thing makes sense. but what's the part about it being \"spooky\"? i saw that phrase somewhere in a textbook, was einstein the one who called it that? how does that actually work in practice if the particles aren't \"decided\" yet?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, Einstein famously called it \"spooky action at a distance\" because it seemed to imply instantaneous communication faster than the speed of light. The \"spookiness\" comes from the non-local nature of the correlation; the measurement on one particle seems to instantaneously influence the state of the other. It's not like sending a signal, though, as you can't use entanglement to send meaningful information faster than light. It's a correlation that is established, not a message that is transmitted.",
      "source": "target",
