    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "idk, it still feels super weird to me. if there's no signal being sent, how can they \"know\" what the other one is doing instantly? it feels like there's some hidden mechanism or something happening behind the scenes that we just can't see with our current math.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That feeling of a hidden mechanism is exactly what troubled many physicists, including Einstein. The prevailing view, supported by Bell's theorem and experiments, is that there is no hidden variable—no secret instruction manual the particles are following. Instead, the particles share a single, unified quantum state until observation forces that state to resolve into definite properties. It's less like them *knowing* and more like they were always part of one interconnected system, even when separated.",
      "source": "target",
